On February 12, 2020, Wuhan had an estimated 3,509 unquarantined infected cases, which decreased to 334 by February 21, 2020. Based on data up to February 21, we predict that COVID-19 in Wuhan and Wuhan will likely end in late March, mid March for the rest of China, and before early March for tier-one cities. In China, it is estimated that 80,511 individuals are infected, with the majority in Wuhan and Wuhan. It is important to note that these estimates are based on a deterministic ODE model and come with some uncertainty.

Our findings suggest that strict quarantine and control measures should remain in place until early March in tier-one cities and late March in Wuhan. Our model can also help predict the epidemic trend and offer guidance to countries at high risk of outbreak like South Korea, Japan, Italy, and Iran. This SUQC model was developed to address the unique characteristics of COVID-19 and has been applied to data from China to forecast the epidemic's trajectory. It can be a valuable tool for other countries facing a potential outbreak.
